, 			{
				"box" : 				{
					"id" : "obj-71",
					"linecount" : 9,
					"maxclass" : "comment",
					"numinlets" : 1,
					"numoutlets" : 0,
					"patching_rect" : [ 361.0, 556.0, 248.0, 127.0 ],
					"text" : "Inlet 1: value x in range [0,1] => [0,1] to map\nInlet 2: sigmoid/logit steepness parameter a\n - a>0: sigmoid(x)\n - a<0: logit(x)\n - a=0: x\nInlet 3: sigmoid/logit shift parameter b [0,1]\n - a>0: shift along x-axis\n - a<0: shift along y-axis\nArgument 1: input scale parameter s: s^(a/s)",
					"textcolor" : [ 0.968627450980392, 0.968627450980392, 0.968627450980392, 1.0 ]
				}

			}
, 			{
				"box" : 				{
					"id" : "obj-45",
					"maxclass" : "comment",
					"numinlets" : 1,
					"numoutlets" : 0,
					"patching_rect" : [ 361.0, 697.625468194484711, 102.0, 20.0 ],
					"text" : "sigmoid/logit(x) =",
					"textcolor" : [ 0.968627450980392, 0.968627450980392, 0.968627450980392, 1.0 ]
				}

			}
, 			{
				"box" : 				{
					"id" : "obj-69",
					"linecount" : 6,
					"maxclass" : "comment",
					"numinlets" : 1,
					"numoutlets" : 0,
					"patching_rect" : [ 17.0, 59.0, 624.0, 87.0 ],
					"text" : "Maps an input to the first inlet to a continuous sigmoid/logit function (S or sideways-S curve) using the algebraic approach with the power function. The steepness of the S curve in both cases can be defined with a parameter in the second inlet. A second parameter defines a shift along either the x-axis or y-axis for more flexibility, depending if a>0 (sigmoid) or a<0 (logit).\nTechnically, the sigmoid function alone could cover both cases a<0 and a>0 and no condition would be necessary. However, for a>0, a then distorts how b affects the curve, so we use the complement logit for consistency."
				}

			}
